<tr>
	<td bgcolor="#F7F7F7" width="175" valign="top" nowrap>
	<a name="post220563"></a>
	
	<font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial"><b>Denec</b></font><br>
	<font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">Templar</font><br>
	<p>
	<font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">Registered: Sep 2003<br>
	Location: <br>
	Posts: 295</font></td>
	
	<td bgcolor="#F7F7F7" width="100%" valign="top">
	<font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial"> <b>Absor posted about casual vs raiding</b></font>
	<p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial"><a href="http://forums.interealms.com/shaman/showthread.php?threadid=21676&mode=linear&perpage=40&pagenumber=4" target="_blank">http://forums.interealms.com/shaman...40&pagenumber=4</a><br />
<br />
<blockquote><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><hr>I have read most of the thread. I'd love to debate this idea with you, but I don't have time right now.<br />
<br />
I agree with you on points and disagree on others. I'll give you a sort of bullet list of my opinions (mine, mind you, not always company policy)<br />
<br />
No, people should not be able to attain the same gear through easier paths (like it or not, group content is easier than raid content, you've given many reasons why it is easier when you state why you don't like it).<br />
<br />
Yes, there should be content for people to do that isn't raiding. Luckily, we have a lot of that.<br />
<br />
If you don't like raiding but you do enjoy playing the game, then there is a lot of content to do with single groups. If you've actually done all of that consider a new character. I've enjoyed starting several characters, different viewpoints are nice.<br />
<br />
Some folks have said things like - people should be able to get similar gear (just make the graphics nicer for the raid people) without raiding. I disagree in principle, as I've said before. I also disagree that this would satisfy those people. The day after such content was added they would be wondering why they don't also get the cool graphics.<br />
<br />
Any game system with progression will have an amount of have's and have-nots. At just about any time in your progression you will be looking at people that have things that you can not attain at that time. That changes as you progress and as the game matures. Note that now players can take major Kunark dragons with a group. That wasn't so when that expansion was put out.<br />
<br />
Stuff that was "raid only" becomes "two groups" and then becomes "single group" content. That's what happens when you have progression.<br />
<br />
I'm just not going to debate the "casual" vs. "uber" thing here. I do want to repeat that if you are a casual player and you spend so much of your time yearning for items or abilities that are out of your reach that you don't enjoy playing, then you're not a casual player. A casual player plays in their free time to have some fun.<br />
<br />
Snoww, you have to understand that we do hear you. We hear a lot of opinions, we read a lot of threads. It's just not possible to build one game that everyone can play the way they want to. We'd need a designer, a coder and an artist for every player. We do our best to make a game that people like to play. We do appreciate your feedback and we do read it. But at some point we have to make decision about how things will work. We want to make you happy just as much as we want to make everyone else happy.<br />
<br />
I have no snappy ending for this. I certainly wrote more than I had planned - so I guess I'm staying late to get some work done . I just wanted you to know that we do understand your point. On the team we'll have as many differing opinions about your ideas as were posted in this thread.<br />
<br />
<br />
<hr></blockquote><br />
<br />
<br />
I have played both casual when i started then become a raider up until I retired.  The only reason I choose raiding was to see the endgame, not because I actually enjoyed it.<br />
<br />
What do you think?</font></p>
	
	<p></p>
	<p></p>
