<tr>
	<td bgcolor="#DEDFDF" width="175" valign="top" nowrap>
	<a name="post220584"></a>
	
	<font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial"><b>ruhbuh</b></font><br>
	<font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">Cleric</font><br>
	<p>
	<font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">Registered: Apr 2004<br>
	Location: <br>
	Posts: 29</font></td>
	
	<td bgcolor="#DEDFDF" width="100%" valign="top">
	<font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial"> <b></b></font>
	<p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">From PoP, EQ has basically become all about the "raider".  In a sense, the way Absor wrote his post, he was saying that once you hit 65, if you don't want to raid, the game is over for you.  Brenlo was quick to follow up with a disclaimer saying that Absor's opinions were his own, but with GoD, the upcoming OoW, and this big push to please the top tier guilds we all could have figured this out on our own.<br />
<br />
For one thing, I would disagree with Absor and say that, as a "casual" (non-raiding) player, I don't really want endgame loot.  Yes, it's cool and desirable, but I understand why it's there and why I don't deserve it if I don't want to raid.  Sure there will always be the "haves" and "have-nots" and sure there will always be someone who complains about this or that, but blanket statements like this are just as ignorant.  <br />
<br />
But if there's anything I really disagree with Absor about most is this comment that the developers cannot create a game that everyone can enjoy.  In a way, they attempted this already when they added in LDoN.  LDoN is not the be all end all as far as content for non-raiders, but it does demonstrate that SoE can create a successful expansion to the game that is scalable to any level and has nothing to do with raiding.  The time-limit instancing is great for people that cannot dump the kind of time it takes to be a raider.  Why not do more of this, but with quests?  Why not turn some "old world" dungeon zones into optional instanced zones or create more instanced zones that aren't part of the LDoN storyline?<br />
<br />
Just because we have a couple of hours in a given night does not mean we are "hardcore" or ready/willing to commit to raiding the way it stands in the game now.<br />
<br />
I think the key to EQ's long term success will be this ability to accomodate non-raiders.  Raiding might seem like the natural evolution of an MMOG centered-upon uberness and kewl phat loot, but like someone in the thread mentioned, it's just an ever-lengthening treadmill with the devs just moving the carrot that much farther away every expansion.  The burnout and frustration that resulted from GoD should be a wake up call that even the most patient and hardworking uber guild has their limits, and that maybe SOE needs to rethink it's future design goals for EQ1 (at least if they plan on supporting it after EQ2).</font></p>
	
	<p></p>
	<p></p>
	<p align="right"><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial"><a href="report.php?s=99c62554b38f1797721c3279c99fed07&postid=220584">Report this post to a moderator</a> | IP: <a href="postings.php?s=99c62554b38f1797721c3279c99fed07&action=getip&postid=220584">Logged</a></font></p>
