	<td bgcolor="#F7F7F7" width="175" valign="top" nowrap>
	<a name="post220585"></a>
	
	<font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial"><b>Reorx</b></font><br>
	<font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">Cleric</font><br>
	<p>
	<font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">Registered: Dec 1999<br>
	Location: Toronto, Canada<br>
	Posts: 41</font></td>
	
	<td bgcolor="#F7F7F7" width="100%" valign="top">
	<font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial"> <b></b></font>
	<p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial"><blockquote><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><hr>No, people should not be able to attain the same gear through easier paths (like it or not, group content is easier than raid content, you've given many reasons why it is easier when you state why you don't like it). <hr></blockquote><br />
<br />
But isn't this exactly what LDoN does? You can do 30 normal adventures at level 65 which, by most standards, are particularily easy, and get yourself a Royal Attendant Breastplate of Sand which, according to Allakhazam's is in the top 10 cleric breastplates (ordered by AC and mana, even if you sort differently it's right up there).  You could rate it even higher since it has 3 aug slots if you wanted.<br />
<br />
IMHO, the Royal Attendant armor is the much easier, not to mention fun, path as opposed to the length of time I'd have to raid (including any flags) to actually have a chance to win a raid chestplate. If I was really eager I could do 15 hard 65 adventures in a few days  to get enough points to buy it...I doubt I could win a raid item in that period.<br />
<br />
Or maybe I misunderstood him and he was referring to something else...just throught it was strange.<br />
<br />
Was thinking that maybe the problem comes from the developers not understanding the differences between a raiding and casual player. It seems a raider plays more for the end goals (new flags, better items, kill the mob, beat the game) while a casual player (like myself) plays more for the moment (to have fun) with the end result not as important as the path taken to get there. They are two different things and I can't see how having the can't support both play styles (as Ruhbuh said very well).</font></p>
	
	<p><p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">__________________<br>
